Introduction

This analysis uses AI to compare the median per year for various IMF metrics of CFA franc zone countries to non-CFA franc zone African countries in the Western and Middle Africa region. The purpose of this analysis is to challenge the claim that the CFA franc zone promotes growth and development. It’s important to note that this analysis does not suggest that the CFA franc is the sole cause of underdevelopment in these countries.

The countries in the CFA franc zone for this analysis are:

WAEMU

  • Benin
  • Burkina Faso
  • Côte d’Ivoire
  • Mali
  • Niger
  • Senegal
  • Togo
  • Guinea Bissau

CEMAC

  • Cameroon
  • Congo
  • Gabon
  • Equatorial Guinea
  • Central African Republic
  • Chad

The non-CFA franc zone countries for this analysis are the countries in the West Africa and Middle Africa region not in the WAEMU or the CEMAC.

West Africa:

  • Cabo Verde
  • The Gambia
  • Ghana
  • Guinea
  • Liberia
  • Mauritania
  • Sierra Leone
  • Nigeria

Middle Africa:

  • São Tomé and Príncipe
  • Angola
  • The Democratic Republic of the Congo

Guinea-Bissau joined the WAEMU in 1997, Mali joined the WAEMU in 1984 and Equatorial Guinea joined the CEMAC in 1985, so any metrics before the year a country joined is considered non-CFA franc zone and any metrics equal to or greater than the year a country joined the CFA franc zone is considered CFA franc zone.

The Comoros is ommited from this analysis, it is part of the East Africa region and uses the Comorian Franc.

Disclaimer

The text below the graphs, labeled “Definition of {indicator}” and “Comparing Median Intervals for indicator {indicator},” is generated by ChatGPT 3.5 using this prompt. The purpose of the prompt is to provide a definition for each indicator and then draw a conclusion comparing the the CFA franc zone and non-CFA franc zone countries based on count in which the median was greater across the yearly intervals for the given indicator. For example, if non-CFA countries had a higher median GDP 18 times out of the 22 yearly intervals between 1980 and 2022, the prompt will draw a conclusion based on that count.

The graphs presented in the “Analysis” section support my challenge to the idea that the CFA franc zone is beneficial for economic growth and development. The graphs in the appendix are created from the same IMF data source with the same prompt.

CFA Franc Zone

The CFA franc, originally the French African Colonial franc, was created in 1945 and imposed on France’s colonies. The CFA franc zone of today is an area of monetary cooperation, comprised of two African economic zones: the West Africa Economic and Monetary Union (WAEMU) and the Central African Economic and Monetary Union (CEMAC), along with Comoros. It should be noted that since 1993, the two CFA francs and the Comorian franc cannot be exchanged for one another. To exchange one currency for the other, it must first be converted to euros. This additional step in conversion creates additional demand for euros, which consequently acts as a privileged intermediary in trade between the African countries. Overall, more than 162 million people use the two CFA francs.

Key decisions concerning the CFA franc zone are made in Paris. The central actor in this system is the French Treasury. All foreign exchange transactions (the purchase or sale of CFA francs) of the 15 countries in the franc zone must go through the French Treasury due to the French guarantee of unlimited convertibility of CFA francs into euros. This makes France the only country in the world that directly manages a set of currencies distinct from its own.

The CFA franc zone is based on four interrelated principles: the fixed exchange rate, the free movement of capital, the free convertibility of the currency, and the centralization of foreign exchange reserves.

Supporters of the CFA franc system suggest that it provides monetary stability, economic attractiveness, investment inflows, and an increase in the growth rate.

The idea that the CFA franc promotes growth and development has been widely touted by the Bank of France. In 2015, the Bank of France stated, “For over forty years, the franc zone has been an instrument of solidarity and development aimed at consolidating growth, reducing poverty, and deepening regional integration.” Additionally, in 2012, Christian Noyer, the governor of the Bank of France, remarked, “The last fifty years have shown that the franc zone is a favorable factor for development.”

However, the CFA franc zone has four major downsides for the countries that are part of it: an excessively rigid exchange rate regime, a problematic pegging to the euro, the underfinancing of African economies, and a free movement of capital that generates a massive financial bleed-out.

GDP Per Capita, Current Prices comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of GDP Per Capita, Current Prices

GDP per capita, measured in U.S. dollars at current prices, provides a meaningful measure of a country’s economic growth and development. It represents the average value, in dollars, of goods and services produced within a country during a specific time period, divided by the average population for the same year. By incorporating both the size of a country’s economy and its population, GDP per capita allows for comparisons of economic performance among countries. This indicator serves as a useful tool for policymakers, investors, and analysts to assess and compare the living standards, productivity levels, and economic progress of different nations. A higher GDP per capita typically indicates higher income levels and better access to goods and services, reflecting a higher standard of living and greater economic prosperity for a country.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator GDP Per Capita, Current Prices

A higher GDP per capita, measured at current prices, is generally seen as an indicator of economic growth and development. It suggests that a country’s citizens have higher purchasing power, access to a wider range of goods and services, and a higher standard of living. Comparing the median GDP per capita, current prices between the CFA franc zone and non-CFA middle/west Africa countries from 1980 to 2023, it is observed that non-CFA countries had more yearly intervals with a higher median. This suggests that these non-CFA countries have experienced relatively stronger economic growth and development in terms of per capita income compared to the countries in the CFA franc zone. The difference in economic performance could be attributed to various factors, including the flexibility of exchange rate regimes, financial autonomy, and the ability to pursue independent monetary policies. However, it is important to conduct further analysis considering other factors such as political stability, infrastructure development, and institutional frameworks to gain a comprehensive understanding of the economic growth trajectory in these regions.

This measure allows for a comparison of GDP between countries by taking into account the differences in prices and purchasing power. By accounting for differences in price levels, PPP adjusts GDP to reflect the real purchasing power of individuals in each country. This provides a more accurate assessment of a country’s economic performance, as it considers the standard of living and the level of economic development. By analyzing GDP Per Capita in PPP terms, policymakers and economists can better understand and compare the economic growth and living standards across different nations.

Implied PPP Conversion Rate comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of Implied PPP Conversion Rate

The concept of Implied PPP Conversion Rate measured in National currency per international dollar is crucial in assessing a country’s economic growth and development. It provides an indicator of the relative overvaluation or undervaluation of a country’s currency in comparison to the international dollar, based on the theory of Purchasing Power Parity (PPP). By comparing the price levels between two countries, changes in the nominal exchange rate can be related to changes in their respective price levels. This measure allows economists to determine whether a country’s currency is over or undervalued, which can have significant implications for its trade balance, competitiveness, and overall economic performance. Consequently, the implied PPP conversion rate serves as a valuable tool for policymakers and analysts in understanding and addressing economic challenges and imbalances.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator Implied PPP Conversion Rate

Higher Implied PPP Conversion Rates have the potential to promote economic growth and development, as they reflect a relatively stronger position of a country’s national currency in comparison to the international dollar. With regards to the CFA franc zone and non-CFA middle/west Africa countries, it is evident from the provided median values that CFA franc zone countries generally experienced more yearly intervals with a higher Implied PPP Conversion Rate over the period from 1980 to 2023. Current Account Balance comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of Current Account Balance

The Current Account Balance, measured in Billions of U.S. dollars, provides valuable insights into a country’s economic growth and development. It encompasses various key components such as exports and imports of goods and services, payments of income, and current transfers between residents and nonresidents. As a comprehensive record of transactions in the balance of payments, the Current Account Balance serves as an indicator of a country’s economic performance and external economic relations. A positive Current Account Balance indicates that the value of goods and services exported exceeds that of imports, reflecting a trade surplus and potential competitive advantage in international markets. Additionally, a surplus implies an inflow of foreign currency, which may contribute to economic growth by enhancing domestic investments. Conversely, a negative Current Account Balance suggests an excess of imports over exports, reflecting a trade deficit that may require foreign borrowing or reduction in domestic investments. Hence, the Current Account Balance, as an indicator of a country’s external economic activity, plays a crucial role in understanding and assessing a country’s economic growth prospects and development trajectory.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator Current Account Balance

Higher Current Account Balance does not necessarily promote economic growth and development. While some proponents argue that a positive Current Account Balance reflects competitive advantages and increased investment inflows, it is important to consider the specific factors contributing to this surplus. In the case of the CFA franc zone countries, the fixed exchange rate regime and the pegging to the euro may restrict the flexibility needed to address economic shocks and promote export competitiveness. On the other hand, non-CFA middle/west Africa countries, with more yearly intervals featuring a higher median Current Account Balance, may have benefited from greater flexibility in managing their exchange rates and pursuing policies that enhance export competitiveness. However, it should be noted that the impact of Current Account Balance on growth and development is multifaceted, and other factors such as fiscal policies, domestic investment, and structural reforms also play significant roles in shaping a country’s economic trajectory.

Primary Net Lending/Borrowing comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of Primary Net Lending/Borrowing

Primary net lending/borrowing measured in % of GDP is a crucial indicator of a country’s economic growth and development. It represents the difference between the government’s total revenue (excluding interest revenue) and its total expenditure (excluding interest expenditure), expressed as a percentage of Gross Domestic Product (GDP). This measure reflects the degree to which a country generates a surplus or deficit in its finances, excluding the impact of interest payments. A positive primary net lending signifies that the government has a surplus, indicating fiscal discipline and the ability to allocate resources towards savings or investments. In contrast, a negative primary net borrowing suggests a deficit, reflecting the need for external funding and potentially indicating a decline in economic stability. Thus, monitoring primary net lending/borrowing as a percentage of GDP allows policymakers and economists to assess a country’s fiscal sustainability, its reliance on external financing, and provides insight into its overall economic health and potential for growth.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator Primary Net Lending/Borrowing

A higher Primary Net Lending/Borrowing has the potential to promote economic growth and development. It signifies that a country is generating a surplus in its finances, allowing for savings, investments, and potential debt reduction. With increased surplus, governments can allocate resources towards infrastructure projects, education, healthcare, and other areas that foster long-term growth. However, when comparing the median Primary Net Lending/Borrowing between CFA franc zone and non-CFA middle/west Africa countries from 1990 to 2023, it is evident that non-CFA middle/west Africa countries had more yearly intervals with a higher median. This suggests that non-CFA middle/west Africa countries might have experienced more favorable conditions for economic growth and development, as reflected in their higher levels of primary net lending/borrowing. Conclusion

In conclusion, non-CFA Middle Africa and West Africa countries consistently had a higher median GDP per capita than CFA franc zone countries and a higher median real GDP growth rate, which tends to be one of the conventional ways to compare economic development between countries. CFA franc zone countries also had a higher median implied PPP conversion rates, suggesting that the currency is overvalued. This overvaluation is expected since both CFA francs in the CFA franc zone are pegged to the euro. An overvalued currency has the effect of making CFA franc zone exports less competitive, thus leading to fewer exports which can hinder the development of domestic production and the domestic economy. This claim is further supported by the consistently higher median of non-CFA countries to CFA franc zone countries when considering the metrics exports of goods and services and overall current account balances. In addition, non-CFA franc zone countries also had much higher levels of net foreign direct investment. This could be in part that their economies are able to attract more net investment and/or non-CFA countries don’t have the same levels of capital flight that CFA franc zone countries have due to the free movement of capital. This ultimately reinforces the challenge to the claim that the CFA franc zone promotes economic growth.

Definition of Current Account Balance

The concept of current account balance, expressed as a percentage of GDP, serves as a crucial indicator of a country’s economic growth and development. It encompasses various transactions within the balance of payments, such as exports and imports of goods and services, income payments, and current transfers between residents and nonresidents. By measuring the current account balance in relation to GDP, it provides insights into a nation’s external economic interactions. A positive current account balance indicates that a country is exporting more goods and services than it is importing, and therefore, is experiencing economic growth. It suggests that the country has a competitive advantage in the global market, leading to increased revenue and employment opportunities. Conversely, a negative current account balance signals that a country is importing more than it is exporting, potentially indicating a need for economic adjustments to improve competitiveness. Thus, examining the current account balance as a percentage of GDP enables policymakers to gauge the overall economic performance and competitiveness of a country, facilitating informed decision-making in pursuit of sustainable economic growth and development.

This metric provides valuable insights into the fiscal health of a nation, as it reflects the excess or deficit funds available for investment or borrowing. Conversely, a negative net lending/borrowing suggests that a country is spending more than its revenue, resulting in a budget deficit. This deficit is typically funded through borrowing, which can lead to increased debt levels. Therefore, monitoring and maintaining a sustainable net lending/borrowing position is crucial for a country’s economic stability and long-term development.

Definition of Real Effective Exchange Rates

The concept of Real Effective Exchange Rates (REER) measured in Annual Average Index, with the base year of 2010 set at 100, provides a valuable indicator of a country’s economic growth and development. REER takes into account the bilateral exchange rates with its trading partners and adjusts them for differences in relative inflation rates. By considering both exchange rate and price level changes, REER captures the competitiveness of a country’s exports and its purchasing power in international markets. A higher REER signifies an appreciation of a country’s currency, indicating decreased competitiveness and potentially hindering export-led growth. Conversely, a lower REER suggests a depreciation of the currency, potentially stimulating economic growth through increased exports. Monitoring and analyzing REER trends is crucial for policymakers to guide appropriate macroeconomic policies and promote sustainable economic development.
